cess and effects of moviemaking, the relationship between the filmmaker and the city, and the film and the spectator. I don't see a common element running through the movies on this list. But they are all seminal works that continue to inform the world of the immense potential and beauty of cinema. ","ref":null,"props":{"children":"To fit the greatest films of all time into a list of ten is impossible. I had to leave out several favourites - Throne of Blood, Passion of Joan of Arc, City of Sadness, The River, Persona, Diamonds of the World and Subarnarekha, to name a few. The list contains my personal favourites and films that I believe played a key role in the history of cinema. I had to rewatch several films, including the inarguably canonised works. Beau Travail, I realised, has grown in beauty over the years; its juxtaposition of the dreamy images of the coast and masculinity trapped in military still holds a great sense of modernness. The uncomplicated humanism of Apur Sansar now appears more powerful than the achievements of Pather Panchali. The profound anger of Princess Mononoke, Studio Ghibli's most audacious work, seems more relevant now than ever. Close-Up and Man With A Movie Camera are two brilliant, audacious works that reflect on the process and effects of moviemaking, the relationship between the filmmaker and the city, and the film and the spectator. I don't see a common element running through the movies on this list. But they are all seminal works that continue to inform the world of the immense potential and beauty of cinema. "},"_owner":null}],"url":"/sight-and-sound/greatest-films-all-time/all-voters/aswathy-gopalakrishnan"},{"firstname":"Belinda","surname":"van de Graaf","slug":"belinda-van-de-graaf","name":"Belinda van de Graaf","sortName":"Graaf, Belinda van de","type":"critic","jobTitle":"Film critic for daily newspaper Trouw","country":"Netherlands","remarks":null,"url":"/sight-and-sound/greatest-films-all-time/all-voters/belinda-van-de-gr